    <h2>3. Cake Display Counters: Selling Refrigeration</h2>
    <p>A cake display counter — also called a pastry display case or chilled display counter — is one of the most important pieces of equipment for any retail bakery or patisserie. It's not just cold storage; it's a sales tool. How your cakes and pastries are displayed directly impacts impulse purchases and average transaction value.</p>
    <p>Display counters maintain temperatures between 2°C and 8°C while offering clear visibility of the products inside. They use forced-air cooling to maintain humidity levels that keep pastry surfaces from drying out, and most have glass on three or four sides for maximum visibility.</p>

    <h3>Types of Cake Display Counters</h3>
    <p><strong>Curved Glass Display Counter:</strong> The classic bakery display with a curved front glass panel. Elegant, good visibility, popular in premium patisseries. Typically 3–6 feet wide. These are the most photogenic displays and work well for premium cake and pastry presentation.</p>
    <p><strong>Straight Glass Display Counter:</strong> More modern, rectangular profile. Easier to clean. Often preferred in contemporary café-bakeries. Available in countertop and floor-standing versions.</p>
    <p><strong>Open-Front Display (Gravity Coil):</strong> Open-top displays without glass doors, typically used for grab-and-go items at 8°C–12°C. Lower cost but less efficient and not suitable for cream-filled products in Indian summer.</p>
    <p><strong>Refrigerated Display Cabinet (Upright):</strong> Glass-door standing units, more like a display fridge than a counter. Used for packaged pastries, beverages, and takeaway items. Good for self-serve retail formats.</p>

