    <h3>Walk-In Cold Room Buying Tips</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Insulation thickness:</strong> Never go below 80mm PU foam in North India. 100mm for freezer rooms.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigeration unit sizing:</strong> The compressor must be sized for worst-case ambient temperature (typically 45°C summer peak) plus load factor. Undersized units will struggle and fail early.</li>
      <li><strong>Floor insulation:</strong> Walk-in cooler floors should be insulated. Many cheap installations skip this — it's a false economy.</li>
      <li><strong>Door heater strip:</strong> Essential for freezer rooms to prevent door frame icing and freezing shut</li>
      <li><strong>Alarm system:</strong> Temperature alarms with SMS/WhatsApp notification are worth the extra ₹5,000–10,000</li>
      <li><strong>Established installer:</strong> Walk-in cold room installation quality varies enormously. Use a supplier with verifiable references in your city.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>7. Energy Ratings and Running Costs</h2>
    <p>Refrigeration is one of the largest electricity consumers in a bakery — running 24/7 unlike ovens and mixers. In India's climate, this cost is even higher because compressors work harder against high ambient temperatures. Understanding energy ratings before you buy can save significant money over a machine's 10–15 year life.</p>

    <h3>BEE Star Ratings for Commercial Refrigerators</h3>
    <p>The Bureau of Energy Efficiency (BEE) rates commercial refrigerators on a 1–5 star scale. A 5-star rated unit uses roughly 40% less electricity than a 1-star unit of the same capacity. For a refrigerator running continuously in a bakery, the difference in electricity cost over 5 years can exceed the difference in purchase price between a budget and premium unit.</p>

