    <h2>8. Refrigeration Needs by Bakery Type</h2>

    <h3>Home Bakery / Small Cloud Kitchen (Budget: ₹30,000–70,000)</h3>
    <p>A 300-litre single-door commercial reach-in refrigerator (₹35,000–55,000) covers most needs. If you're making cream cakes or pastries that need display, consider a small 3-ft display counter. Avoid domestic refrigerators — they're not built for continuous operation in hot kitchen conditions.</p>

    <h3>Small Retail Bakery (Budget: ₹1L–2.5L)</h3>
    <p>You'll need: one double-door reach-in for ingredients (₹70,000–1,00,000) + one 4-ft cake display counter (₹65,000–95,000). Total: ₹1.3L–2L. If budget allows, add a small undercounter for the prep area.</p>

    <h3>Medium Bakery / Patisserie (Budget: ₹2.5L–6L)</h3>
    <p>Double-door reach-in for ingredients + blast chiller + 5–6 ft display counter. Possibly a retarder-proofer if you bake artisan breads. Budget ₹3.5L–6L for this setup. The blast chiller is the key differentiator at this level — it protects cream-based product quality and extends shelf life.</p>

    <h3>Large Commercial Bakery (Budget: ₹6L–15L)</h3>
    <p>Walk-in cold room for ingredients, blast chiller, display counters in the retail section, possibly a separate freezer room for frozen product. A well-planned large bakery refrigeration setup at this level handles hundreds of kilos of product daily.</p>

    <h2>9. Things to Check Before Buying Bakery Refrigeration in India</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tropical-rated compressor:</strong> Verify the unit is rated for ambient temperatures up to 43°C (tropical climate class T). Many budget units are only rated to 32°C or 38°C and will struggle in Indian summers.</li>
      <li><strong>Service network:</strong> Can the brand's authorised service technician reach you within 24 hours? In peak summer, a failed refrigerator is a crisis. Ask for the nearest service centre location before buying.</li>
      <li><strong>Warranty terms:</strong> Commercial refrigerators should carry at minimum a 1-year comprehensive warranty and 3–5 years on the compressor. Read the fine print — some warranties exclude commercial use.</li>
      <li><strong>Power supply requirements:</strong> Large reach-in units and walk-in rooms may require three-phase power. Confirm before ordering.</li>
      <li><strong>Voltage stabiliser:</strong> In areas with voltage fluctuation (much of non-metro India), a stabiliser is essential to protect commercial refrigerator compressors. Budget ₹3,000–8,000 for a stabiliser.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant type:</strong> Newer units use R290 (hydrocarbon) or R600a refrigerants that are more environmentally friendly and more efficient than older R134a/R404A refrigerants. Check what refrigerant is used — it affects future servicing costs.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>10. New vs. Used Commercial Refrigerators</h2>
    <p>Used commercial refrigerators in good condition can be found for 40–60% of new price through OLX, local equipment dealers, and hotel/restaurant auctions. A well-maintained 5-year-old True or Blue Star reach-in refrigerator can still have 8–10 years of service life remaining.</p>
    <p>However, be cautious with used refrigeration. Check the compressor ampere draw (should match the nameplate specification), inspect door seals carefully, verify the thermostat accuracy with a separate thermometer, and ask about the refrigerant type — some older units use R22 which is now prohibited in India.</p>
    <p>Walk-in cold rooms that are being decommissioned can be purchased and reinstalled, potentially saving 50%+ on new cost. This requires careful panel inspection for delamination or moisture intrusion, and the refrigeration unit may need servicing or replacement.</p>

