      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What temperature should a bakery refrigerator be set at? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">For general ingredient storage (butter, eggs, dairy, fruit fillings), set at 3°C–5°C. For cake display and pastry display, 2°C–6°C is standard. Walk-in cold rooms for ingredient storage typically run at 0°C–4°C. Freezer rooms for frozen dough and frozen cakes should run at -18°C to -22°C. Always verify actual temperatures with a calibrated thermometer placed in the warmest part of the unit (usually the top shelf or door area).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do I need a blast chiller for my bakery? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A blast chiller is not essential for a basic bakery but becomes important if you're producing cream-based pastries, mousses, entremets, or any product with a short food-safety window. It's also very useful for production efficiency — you can bake, blast chill, and store same-day product rather than having products occupy oven space while cooling gradually. For serious patisserie work, a blast chiller at ₹1.5L–3L is a worthwhile investment.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much electricity does a commercial bakery refrigerator use in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A typical 400 L commercial reach-in refrigerator draws 300–500W, costing ₹10,000–17,000 annually at ₹8/kWh. A cake display counter (4 ft) adds another ₹14,000–21,000/year. In Indian summers, compressors work harder and costs are higher. Choosing BEE 4-5 star rated units and inverter-technology compressors can cut these costs by 25–40%.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

